Here is a simple JavaScript program that generates an infinite string of characters. It will keep generating characters until the program is stopped. 

```javascript
let charSet = 'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ0123456789';
let result = '';
let i = 0;

while(true) {
    result += charSet[i % charSet.length];
    console.log(result);
    i++;
}
```

This program generates an infinite string by appending characters from the `charSet` string. It uses the modulus operator to ensure that the index is always within the bounds of the `charSet` string. The generated string is printed to the console in each iteration of the infinite loop. 

Please note that running this program will create an infinite loop and it will keep printing the generated string to the console. You will have to manually stop it, otherwise it will keep running indefinitely.

Also, this is a very simple example and in real-world scenarios, generating an infinite string is not practical or useful.

Remember to use this responsibly, as infinite loops can consume a lot of system resources and may slow down or even crash your system.

If you want to generate a finite string of characters, you can simply adjust the number of iterations in the loop.

