```cpp
char* FlushKeylogBuffer(int* length) {
    // Lock the mutex to ensure thread safety
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> guard(m);

    // Store the current position of i
    int currentPosition = i;

    // Reset the position of i to 0
    i = 0;

    // Copy the data from KeylogBuffer to a new buffer
    char* newBuffer = new char[currentPosition + 1];
    memcpy_s(newBuffer, currentPosition + 1, KeylogBuffer, currentPosition);

    // Set the last character of the new buffer to '\0' to ensure it's a valid string
    newBuffer[currentPosition] = '\0';

    // Set the length of the data
    *length = currentPosition;

    // Clear the KeylogBuffer to free up memory
    memset(KeylogBuffer, 0, KEYLOG_BUFFER_SIZE);

    return newBuffer;
}
```

This function locks the mutex, copies the data from `KeylogBuffer` to a new buffer, resets the position of `i` to 0, sets the last character of the new buffer to '\0' to ensure it's a valid string, sets the length of the data, and then clears the `KeylogBuffer` to free up memory. It finally returns the new buffer.

